name: Thuy Phap - Ecole Claire Joie
metadata: {'@context': 'http://schema.org', '@type': 'LocalBusiness', 'name': 'Thuy Phap - Ecole Claire Joie', 'description': 'Le Thuy Phap, litt√©ralement "m√©thode de l'eau", est une pratique ancestrale des vietnamiens √† la recherche du bien-√™tre au quotidien, inspir√©e des mouvements de labeur des paysans et p√™cheurs qui, gr√¢ce au mim√©tisme aquatique, se forgent une sant√© de fer. Les pratiquants apprennent √† utiliser la masse liquide du corps humain par des enchainements de mouvements circulaires, bien coordonn√©s et fluides, en veillant √† la justesse de la respiration. La pratique du Thuy Phap, remarquable m√©thode anti-stress, vise √† faire circuler les flux de l'√©nergie vitale en renfor√ßant le m√©tabolisme. D'un point de vue technique, l'approche particuli√®re de cet art martial dit "interne" ou "doux" pr√©f√®re la juste lib√©ration de l'√©nergie √† la puissance de la force musculaire. Il est appr√©ci√© √† tout age, aussi bien par ceux qui souhaitent conserver la souplesse, am√©liorer le tonus et renforcer la sant√© que ceux qui recherchent les exercices plus toniques, les combats codifi√©s ou la pratique des armes. ____________________ Thuy Phap, literally "water method", is an ancestral practice of the Vietnamese in search of daily well-being, inspired by the labor movements of peasants and fishermen who, thanks to aquatic mimicry, build up physical stamina and fortitude. Practitioners learn how to use the liquid mass of the human body through sequences of circular, well-coordinated and fluid movements, paying attention to correct breathing. The practice of Thuy Phap, a remarkable anti-stress method, aims to circulate the flow of vital energy by strengthening the metabolism. From a technical point of view, the particular approach of this so-called "internal" or "soft" martial art prefers the right release of energy to the power of muscular strength. It is appreciated at all ages, both by those who wish to maintain flexibility, improve tone and strengthen health as well as those who are looking for more tonic exercises, codified combat or the practice of weapons.', 'address': {'@type': 'PostalAddress', 'addressLocality': 'Bruxelles, Belgium', 'addressCountry': 'Belgium', 'postalCode': '1040', 'streetAddress': 'Ecole claire joie, Rue Beckers 131'}, 'telephone': '+32 474 63 91 68', 'geo': {'@type': 'GeoCoordinates', 'latitude': '50.8282891', 'longitude': '4.3844153'}, 'priceRange': '-', 'image': 'https://storage.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/usc-pro-uscweb-live-media/o/de-live%2Foriginal_1200x675_IMG_20181127_193819_1578488407108306_admin.jpg?alt=media'}
description: Le Thuy Phap, litt√©ralement "m√©thode de l'eau", est une pratique ancestrale des vietnamiens √† la recherche du bien-√™tre au quotidien, inspir√©e des mouvements de labeur des paysans et p√™cheurs qui, gr√¢ce au mim√©tisme aquatique, se forgent une sant√© de fer. Les pratiquants apprennent √† utiliser la masse liquide du corps humain par des enchainements de mouvements circulaires, bien coordonn√©s et fluides, en veillant √† la justesse de la respiration. La pratique du Thuy Phap, remarquable m√©thode anti-stress, vise √† faire circuler les flux de l'√©nergie vitale en renfor√ßant le m√©tabolisme. D'un point de vue technique, l'approche particuli√®re de cet art martial dit "interne" ou "doux" pr√©f√®re la juste lib√©ration de l'√©nergie √† la puissance de la force musculaire. Il est appr√©ci√© √† tout age, aussi bien par ceux qui souhaitent conserver la souplesse, am√©liorer le tonus et renforcer la sant√© que ceux qui recherchent les exercices plus toniques, les combats codifi√©s ou la pratique des armes. ____________________ Thuy Phap, literally "water method", is an ancestral practice of the Vietnamese in search of daily well-being, inspired by the labor movements of peasants and fishermen who, thanks to aquatic mimicry, build up physical stamina and fortitude. Practitioners learn how to use the liquid mass of the human body through sequences of circular, well-coordinated and fluid movements, paying attention to correct breathing. The practice of Thuy Phap, a remarkable anti-stress method, aims to circulate the flow of vital energy by strengthening the metabolism. From a technical point of view, the particular approach of this so-called "internal" or "soft" martial art prefers the right release of energy to the power of muscular strength. It is appreciated at all ages, both by those who wish to maintain flexibility, improve tone and strengthen health as well as those who are looking for more tonic exercises, codified combat or the practice of weapons.
